<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-636-236  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 636 236.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Sept 1989 v14 n9 p259(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Serving up data: can centralized data preserve the independence ofindividual users?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Name, Mark L.; Catchings, Bill.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Support for multiple simultaneous users is one of the biggestadvantages of the database server over traditional stand-alonemicrocomputer database systems.andP;  The database server cuts down ondata redundancy and inconsistency by storing a single copy of eachpiece of information, providing all users with access to changesin the data.andP;  The database server is essentially a compromisebetween current microcomputer-based systems and the centralizeddatabase systems of mainframes and minicomputers.andP;  Centralizeddata storage makes database backup easier and provides amanageable solution to the problem of security.andP;  The client-serverarchitecture also provides the advantages of multiple hardware andsoftware platforms.andP;  They do remove the independence of themicrocomputer user and place control in the hands ofadministrators.andP;  And if the central server goes down, all accessto data is lost.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsData Base ServersStructured Query LanguageFunction Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>